arch:property.oc:show_val: Covered by Locus 4 Fill/Debris. Built up to and covers the lower half of the Scalarion Loci 8 and 11 and the Cunei Loci 7 and 9. Covers the Scalarion Locus 10, the Orchestra Retaining Wall Locus 12, and the Locus 13 Fill/Debris. Equal to Loci 4 and 13 Fill/Debris.
Phase XII: Use levels, robbing and abandonments continue.
Bottom elevation: 906.806 m at the north, 906.836 m at the center, 906.736 m at the southeast.
Top elevation: 907.586 m at the north, 907.496 m at the south.

Phase IX: Major CE 363 earthquake leads to the collapse of major temple architectural elements including the West Porch columns. Collapse and accumulation of debris around the temple east columns and on top of the lower risers of interior and rear staircases. Buckling of the west intercolumnar wall. Possible conflagration. Primary fluvial layer is deposited.

Fill/Debris within the Theater, above the level of the Pulpitum Wall Locus 14 at the north and the Orchestra Retaining Wall Locus 12 at the south and up to the level of the lowest tier of seating in the Cuneous Locus 7. This locus consists of large stone architectural debris with sandy fill - equal to Locus 13 below it. The vast majority of architectural fragments found in this locus belong to columns and their capitals which fell from the West Colonnade. Several fragments of decorative plaster were found Â— white fluted plaster from the columns and green painted wall plaster from the Theater itself (see Locus 13 above). Some indication of the architectural decoration in this area of the Temple was indicated by the discovery of two carved stone bosses in the form of a single pine cone surrounded by a leaf halo. They are identical to the pine cone bosses from the capitals except that they attached from the back instead of from the base and so were probably used as wall decoration. Unfortunately, their context (i.e., mixed in the collapse rubble) does not inform us about their original placement in the room. The possibility of a carved relief decorating the area of the Pulpitum, is suggested by a fragment of a pedestal in relief found in the debris directly above the central area of the Pulpitum Wall Locus 14. (Seq. 47122).
Phase XI: Further collapse post CE 5th c., possibly the result of the earthquake of CE 512. The east Porch columns and Central Arch collapse and fluvial deposits continue to accumulate.

Phase X: Site abandonment post major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c, Upper level robbing occurs including the upper treads of East and West Interior and Rear Staircases, and the associated upper landings. Evidence of squatter camps in the South Corridor and Central Arch.
Phase XIII: Major collapses continue into the Islamic period.
Measurements: 9.80 m in length (north-south), 4.90 m in width (east-west); 0.76 m (south) and 0.78 north.) in depth.
Major collapse of the temple structure and the accumulation of architectural debris over the orchestra floor and the lower Theater seats.
